body:
Hi @Oxi84,
Please make sure you have only onnxruntime-gpu installed. Have you also installed onnxruntime (CPU-only)? If so, could you please `pip uninstall -y onnxruntime && pip uninstall -y onnxruntime-gpu && pip install onnxruntime-gpu` and try again? Thank you.

Hi, @jcwchen, @Oxi84 .  
I face same problem, and I found this Bug is fixed (for the issue that fails GPU execution if the executable is on the path that contained the unicode characters) in 1.9.1, 
[https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/releases/tag/v1.9.1](url)

but I don't know how to install 1.9.1 from the source code in the link. 
May you give me some guidance? Thanks a lot

Hi @Liubinggunzu,
Do you use Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning NuGet package? IIUC, 1.9.1 patch only fixes the issue for that NuGet package: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/9229

If so, the package link is here: https://www.nuget.org/packages/Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning/. If not, there might be other issue causing it. Thanks.

Hi @jcwchen,

Sorry that I misread that. I  don't use Microsoft.AI.MachineLearning NuGet package. 
But I uninstalled and reinstall onnxruntime-gpu 1.9.0.  This problem still exist. 

My environment is cuda11.0,  Ubuntu 18.04.5

No worries. Then please check your CUDA and CuDNN versions. They must be compatible to each other. Here is the link which might be helpful: https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/execution-providers/CUDA-ExecutionProvider.html For ONNXRuntime 1.9.0 package, I think it was built by CUDA 11.4. Ideally it should support 11.x with the minimum required driver version... I will confirm with the team which CUDA version the minimum required is for ORT 1.9.0 and let you know (as below). Thank you!

Update:
ORT 1.9.0 support support CUDA 11.0+. (1.9.0 release note also mentioned it) https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/execution-providers/CUDA-ExecutionProvider.html The matrix here will be updated soon. Thanks.


BTW, if you are looking for a way to build ORT from source with CUDA EP, here is the tutorial: https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/build/eps.html#cuda.

> 
> 
> Hi @Oxi84, Please make sure you have only onnxruntime-gpu installed. Have you also installed onnxruntime (CPU-only)? If so, could you please `pip uninstall -y onnxruntime && pip uninstall -y onnxruntime-gpu && pip install onnxruntime-gpu` and try again? Thank you.

Thank you for answering. 

I did install only onnxruntime-gpu and when i do: print(onnxruntime.version) i get 1.9.0
print(onnxruntime.get_device()) gives me GPU
print(the_session.get_providers()) gives me CPUexecution

All is installed in an anacodan envinronment, so every anaconda environment has its own version of cuda and this one has cuda 10.2 not sure which CUDNN.

Do i need to install another version of onnxruntime that is compatible with cuda 10.2?

Also it is possible that it onxxruntime tries to use system's Cuda and not the one from the conda envinronment, even for example pytorch detects and uses the right version of cuda.

> 
> 
> Hi, @jcwchen, @Oxi84 . I face same problem, and I found this Bug is fixed (for the issue that fails GPU execution if the executable is on the path that contained the unicode characters) in 1.9.1, [https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/releases/tag/v1.9.1](url)
> 
> but I don't know how to install 1.9.1 from the source code in the link. May you give me some guidance? Thanks a lot

Do you get GPU as device  - print(onnxruntime.get_device()) gives me GPU
I cannot install older version using line  pip install onnxruntime-gpu-1.8.1, is there any other way to do this as I have found cuda 10.2 was faster than 11 and 11.2 last time i checked.

@Oxi84, I think it is because corresponding CUDA and cuDNN is not installed. It is possible to use system's CUDA as long as you set path environment variable correctly even when the conda has older version of CUDA. If everything is good, `print(the_session.get_providers())` shall show `['CUDAExecutionProvider', 'CPUExecutionProvider']`

Official onnxruntime-gpu 1.8.1 need CUDA 11.0. You can try install like ``pip install onnxruntime-gpu==1.8.1``. Or build from source like
```
export CUDACXX="/usr/local/cuda/bin/nvcc"

sh build.sh --config Release  --build_shared_lib --parallel  --use_cuda --cuda_version  11.0 --cuda_home /usr/local/cuda --cudnn_home /usr/local/cuda --build_wheel --skip_test --cmake_path /usr/local/bin/cmake 
```

When the issue is resolved, I suggest you try our [transformers optimizer](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/tree/master/onnxruntime/python/tools/transformers#readme) to speed up the inference like
```
from onnxruntime.transformers import optimizer
optimized_model = optimizer.optimize_model("/root/Desktop/onnx/robertabase.onnx", model_type='bert')
optimized_model.save_model_to_file("/root/Desktop/onnx/optimized_robertabase.onnx")

```

What speedup could I expect from ONNX for Roberta or Bert if batch size is around 10 and sequence is around 60 on average?

Anyways, will try a clean system install. I use anaconda and then i install cuda only in virtual environments, i guess there is no way to use it as a system cuda when declaring it in some environment variable?

I use the optimiser in the exact way you showed, I get around 10+ percent speedup from it on CPU. So totally it is around 33 percent of speedup. 4 sec without and 3 sec with ONNX for batch size 10 on CPU which is the fastest.

> I cannot install older version using line pip install onnxruntime-gpu-1.8.1, is there any other way to do this as I have found cuda 10.2 was faster than 11 and 11.2 last time i checked.

There are still pre-build onnxruntime-gpu that support  cuda10.2 + cudnn8, please uninstall the onnxruntime-gpu firstly, then reinstall as below

```bash
pip3 install onnxruntime-gpu==1.6.0
```
